My Post February 2023 Banlist Here's my Galaxy-Eyes deck updated to face the new format and meta.

By using the effect of "Greed", your opponent will continually take damage as they are forced to draw cards outside of their Draw Phase. "Broken Blocker" helps replace "Defender", "Shield Wing", or "Glow Moss" if they're ever destroyed in battle, while "Dark Door" limits the number of opponent attacks per turn to one, making "Shield Wing" unable to be destroyed by battle. "Cat of Ill Omen" and "Booby Trap E" can retrieve "Greed" if it's removed, and "Galaxy Cyclone" can remove spells/traps that negate "Greed", such as "Royal Decree".

New format idea: ARCHYTIPAL CARDS ONLY

The deck building rules are as follows:

1. 40-60 card main(maybe a smaller deck size can be allowed to allow smaller archytipes to be legal), ≥15 extra and side

2.Up to 3 archytipes in a deck

   - the 3 archytipes must be correlated,at least a card in common (I'm still think about this rule,maybe it's too much)

   - cards that are part of multiple archytipes don't count towards the archytipe number limit( example: you can run tri-brigade mercourier in branded-despia-bystial even tho its also part of the Tri archytipe because it mentions fallen of albaz) 

   - cards in the side deck don't count towards the archytipe number limit(as long as of course,the rules is upheld post side)

3. No cards that aren't part of the respective archytipes

   - exceptions are cards that are mentioned in the archytipal cards(example:hungry burger in nouvellez)

   - cards that have achytipal cards in the artwork(archfiend glitch has labrynth monsters in it,therefore archyfiend cards can be played in labrynth XD)

4. No banlist( might remove later :)

Here's a sample albaz-despia-bysatial I scraped together. Let me know what you think and would be glad if more people build decks for this "format"

My discord if for some reason you need it: RaykiruShiroyshi;향#7179(tho I'm logged in ygopro through discord anyway)

In total, the deck is pretty good for its price at slowing down the game and manipulating the board state in your favor. The deck isn't the most consistent but it gives an enjoyable playing experience if you enjoy control decks.

Libromancers rely on having ritual monsters in hand to function

Nekroz and Mikanko ritual monsters are both a semi 1 hand starter hence this is one of the best ways to utilize rituals with less chances of bricking

Choju is a godsent support for rituals allowing the search of  any ritual monster and spell. the only downside is its a normal summon but since none of libromancer nekroz and mikanko technically need their normal summon Choju is a option.

Of course there is diviner but you cant search 2 without using going through the Exa-bettle line and then youll need another lvl6 for that too, which is one of doombroker/agent/ohime and I personally dislike the Archlord floodgate or Baronne in every deck idea :x

Choju is bascially like junk speeder for rituals.

Because the deck has many ways to start it can bait out some hand traps and negates. but overall the deck isnt very good but fun enough to play.

Feel free to leave feed back and suggestions :D

deck_excerpt: Banish the entire field... multiple times!
deck_description:
Hello welcome to my recent Ghoti deck profile. I have to say I am in love with this deck. You can push OTK's very easily, make multiple interruptions first turn, banish your opponennts field up to two times and even have inbuild handtrap mechanics. It also can play around handtraps.

If you are not familiar with this deck, you need to get into " Superancient Deepsea King Coelacanth" thorugh making "Abyss Keeper" and using it's effect. Alternatively you can specialsummon " Superancient Deepsea King Coelacanth" by the effect of "Paces, Light of Ghoti". If you believe your opponennt has a targeting monster effect negation waiting for you, you can specialsummon one fish-type monster additionally to counter things such like as "Infinite Impermanence", "Effect Veiler" or "Forbidden Chalice". After " Superancient Deepsea King Coelacanth" resoves you need to specialsummon every other Ghoti-tuner monster and "Fishborg Launcher". Then you can make "White Aura Monoceros" and go off to the races. 

If you go second and you have "Zep, Rubin of Ghoti" and "Snopios, Shade of Ghoti", you interrupt your opponennt by using the effect of "Snopios, Shade of Ghoti" to banish "Zep, Rubin of Ghoti" and one more fish-type monster to special summon both of them. Now you can decide if you want a Raigeki-effect ("White Aura Whale") or a banish snipe ("Askaan, the Bicorned Ghoti"). 

When "Paces, Light of Ghoti" and "Shif, Fairy of Ghoti" get banished in your turn, they come back to the field in next Standy Phase. If you have additionally "Snopios, Shade of Ghoti" and "Zep, Rubin of Ghoti" and one "Arionpos, Serpent of Ghoti" on the field, you can make up to two "Ghoti, Deep Beyond" in your opponennts turn which means two times field banish. 

Comment if you want me to explain the full combo. Thanks for reading and have fun with this deck.

pend best deck (still in 2023)

Dark Magician has finally received the support cards that were released in the TCG in Battle of Chaos over a year ago and sadly its a little too late, as they came out at the same time as the Spright archetype and Tearlaments are getting closer, DM will have little room to enjoy even rogue play; additionally, because Predaplant Verte Anaconda is still legal, Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon remains banned drastically reducing the power level that the deck has compared to the TCG. All of this being said, Dark Magician is still a fun deck and does benefit from the new cards, first of all Illusion of Chaos (IOC) offers the deck a huge boost in consistency, being able to access both Magician's Rod and Magicians' Souls more often, IOC can also search Timaeus the United Dragon, another new card, which can be used to fusion summon Dark Magician the Dragon Knight or even Mysterion the Dragon Crown (A spicy extra deck option I like to play), no longer do you need to rely on hard drawing The Eye of Timaeus or running Keeper of Dragon Magic (Which conflicts with Rod for the normal summon) for fusion plays; as far as power goes, Master of Chaos is a new boss monster that on paper looks strong but I at least find myself rarely using it. Concerning my list in particular, I like to play 3 Secrets of Dark Magic instead of just 1 because I hate being out of searches/draws and still not having access to it, I love it both turn one to fusion summon Dragon Knight or Mysterion or even ritual summon IOC for the monster negate and then turn 2 to get more damage in, worst case scenario they can be used as cost for IOC, Souls or Timaeus; I also play some copies of Piercing the Darkness which is very strong alongside a Dragon Knight and Eternal Soul, these two protect each other from effects and Piercing the Darkness protects Dragon Knight in battle.

deck_excerpt: Normal Summoning Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio for full combo!
deck_description:
Predaplant Engine is used to search Instant Fusion  or if you have that already on your hand, you can search Fusion Destiny instead (or Ready Fusion, just and idea). Also, Predaplant is a tasty food for Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown  <3

Lonefire Blossom is optional (it can make Beagram easier to summon later).
2 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra  is recommended so it's not awkward when you draw one.
Crossout Designator  is recommended (don't forget to add the targets as well).

And do you know that Cruel Saturn is a Dark monster, so you can summon him using Predaplant Bufolicula :)

The combo starts by normal summoning Scorpio (discard 1 Monster), SP Cobra to add Instant Fusion. Then, Make Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss  to dump Beetrooper Scout Buggy. Active Instant Fusion to summon Beetrooper Cruel Saturn and add Beetrooper Assault Roller. Summon Roller by banishing Scout Buggy and that'll trigger Saturn to summon Scout Buggy.

Contact "C"  is relevant againts Kashtira, but you can always replace them with something else, Artifact Lancea  for example.

deck_excerpt: Kashtira ( Banish man format, my 3 months experience )
deck_description:
yo everyone this is Lohamora again, well my plan was to make Spright Gishki and new Tear for post-photon hypernova but the ban list surprised me before we go into the best Kashtira deck list, remind you to check out my Branded Bystial deck for post-photon-hypernova

so like all my other deck lists here are some notes ( I'm sure everybody knows the basic combos in the deck so far, I'll explain a few tech cards this time)

Planet pathfinder: so since we rarely normal summon in this deck and field spell for its own is a one-card combo, this card becomes the best card to play for our normal summon, but playing 3 copies of this card, sounded too bricky since sometimes you need your ns for Kashtira birth, so I added 2 copies of this card along side of Triple Tactics Thrust instead of a third copy.

Book of Eclipse: well this card happens to be the best board breaker for post-photon hypernova, but be aware that this card can get ashed, so that's the main reason why we run ash in our Kashtira deck. 

Knightmare Iblee and Linguriboh: well these cards help the deck a lot, they stop your opponent from using Nibiru or using Imperm, It's also a big heavy lock against many decks, especially against Kashtira, however, it's weak against Floowandereeze, and Linguriboh can negate traps, they are best combination cards

Infinitrack Goliath: you can banish this card as one of the targets for the pot of prosperity, then you can attach this card to Arise-heart as its materials, so Arise-heart can not be destroyed by card effects, which makes it too annoying to out.

Elder Entity N'tss: again you can banish this card as one of the targets for the pot of prosperity, then you can attach this card to Arise-heart as its materials, so if your opponent uses your Arise-heart as a super poly target, you can trigger Elder's effect to destroy 1 card on the field by targeting the card.

Artifact Lancea: the best card for Kashtira mirror matches

now now, since we are done explaining a few notes about cards in the deck, let's go for some rulings checks

What happens if you had Unicorn on the field and then you used Kashtira theosis to special summon a Kashtira monster with a different name, and your opponent somehow destroys your Unicorn ( for example he uses branded beast's effect to pop your Unicorn )? well the effect Kashtira theosis won't work, since there is no longer a Kashtira monster on the field. ( if you had to pop a card on the field, I would recommend you not pop Presurred planet Wraitsoth but pop the Kashtira unicorn instead, when they tried to use Kashtira theosis cuz they could already have Unicorn on their hand )

Will my zones get unlocked if I negate Shangri-lra's effects? well, the effect says, that this card should be face-up on the field to use its effects, doesn't matters if it's negated or not negated.

can I tribute my planet pathfinder, after my opponent used Imperm to negate its effect before I use the effect? yes you can, cuz this card tributes for a cost ( this card is really nice, not only a combo starter but it's also a negate baiter )

now in this section, we are going to give you the best card names to use against Kashtira and defeat them.

evenly matched - book of the eclipse - lava golem - Kurikara ( this card is broken against Kashtira ) - Contact "C" ( use this card after they used Kashtira theosis ) - Artifact Lancea - dimensional Barrier 

how to side in this deck

GOING FIRST
well we have Iblee + Lancea ( you can run dimensional fissure in your side deck instead if you want to )

GOING SECOND
well this deck, happens to be one of the best second-going decks
you have lava golem + evenly matched + pankratops + lightning storm 

now that we are over with the list and notes and rulings and siding let's go to the final talk

this deck is a strong anti-meta-based deck, it is also one of the annoying decks in-game same as Floowandereeze, personally, i don't like where this game is going in TCG, we are getting more floodgates out, and it's not healthy, don't ever think Floowandereeze lost barrier doesn't means they won't win (apparently, they are using Fossil Dyna with the small world, and some Simorgh cards to extend their floodgate summoning mode), playing Kashtira in the first week when it got released in OCG was fun, but now it doesn't sound fun anymore.

well good luck duelists, hope you can enjoy this banish-man format ( if you can find any joy in this Toxic format )

See you guys on my deck lists for post-Cyber storm Accel

Flamvell Firedog is just about my favorite Yu-Gi-Oh card of all time. Probably because I gave away my cards when I was younger (only had a few somewhat expensive cards, nothing too crazy) and it's one of the few cards I still have from my childhood. So a deck using Flamvell Firedog was the first Edison deck I submitted on this site. It was heavily inspired by another deck (I think/hope I mentioned that. Edit: Yeah I did, at the end) and so is this one. I made a few changes but after a quite gimmicky deck last time I'm happy to say that I think this deck really does it. It's pretty much Diva HERO. It's consistent, has many strong plays and a Spell Card that is way too broken. If you want endorphins, this is how you get them.

The plan this time is to mill Flamvell monsters with Ryke, Charge and Card Trooper, still with the intent to Normal Summon Firedog to destroy a monster and trigger its effect. Book of Moon is a fantastic, universal tool to help you with that.

Now every deck I've ever seen plays 3 Flamvell Magician and I never unterstood why. I still don't so I cut it down to two copies. I brick on it much less and it just feels so much better. Occasionally you won't be able to trigger Firedog but who cares, that just means your GY is stacked.

The Gravekeeper cards help with your board presence, are a removal tool and all have the DARK attribute. This makes summoning Chaos Sorcerer and Dark Armed Dragon quite easy.

Deck I used for orientation:https://www.edisonformat.com/decks/edison-legends-6th

deck_excerpt: Konami made more Level 3 warriors? sign me up!
deck_description:
The recently added MIkanko archetype in Amazing Defenders is an Equip-based warrior archetype that was originally designed to be a towers.dek focused strategy.

With this, we are completely going to ignore all of that in favor for the cards that give us a lot of gas. Why are we doing this? Since Kashtira is a big meta threat and that deck dies to nibiru, we need something to help us gas through it (and by extention also gas past many other forms of handtraps.) This is where the mikanko package comes in! With Isolde, we can use it to summon renaud, sending a copy of arabesque, renaud will fetch the arabesque from the GY which will let us get Ha-Re from deck, this level 3 warrior can let us grab Fire Dance, another equip spell that lets us summon a mikanko from hand or GY.

with all of this extention we have so much gas that we can end on practically any board we want. In this build, I'm personally not going too crazy with it as saving stuff like your Fire Dance for the crackback is so much more effective. Even though I'm not going crazy with it, that doesn't mean the turn 1 endboards are anything to scoff at, enter Knightmare Gryphon! 

Knightmare Gryphon is a really power piece to end your board on because of it's second effect to basically just be a skill drain on legs. This means it outright kills any deck that doesn't play too many links, I;e EVERY META DECK THIS FORMAT!!! Kash? dead, Branded? Hella dead, Swordsoul? you best believe it's dead! Spright? they have to try pretty hard to get anything done.

And last but not least, since this endboard is almost entirely links, you're immune to all of the book of moon-type cards that people are bound to be main-decking for Kashtira!

But, with all good things, there are the bad. First off, this build has a horrendus matchup vs Kashtira and Labrynth going second. and lastly, Artifact Lancea, Chaos Hunter and Dimension Shitter still rain on your parade, but at least 2 of those 3 also cripple Kashtira!

So what do ya say? are you willing to take on the challenge? Command these ghostly warriors to your victory!

deck_excerpt: Fun Fact: All of the Purrely quick play spells discard for effect!
deck_description:
Dark World Purrely

The synergy between these decks are fairly simple, Purrely needs good cards to discard so that they don't run out of advantage, and Dark world needs additional cards to discard themselves. Dark worlds provide near-infinite discard fodder for your purrely quick plays, as well as link material for an Apollousa or Muckracker, rank 8 material for 38 or 90, or to make a fusion that can negate 1 card, then get rid of 2 cards in the opponent's hand. The Dark worlds also provide a great drawing engine so you can get access to your Purrely quick-play spells without relying on the randomness of Purrely (25550531). The new Purrely card, Purrely Lily (79933029), gives a great boost to the deck. It allows you to play less copies of My Friend Purrely (56700100) since it can search any Purrely non-quick-play spell Purrely, which can turn almost any purrely card into a one-card combo for Expurrely Noir (83827392). 

 

In order to play the deck, you will have to be familiar with Dark World with the new support, as there are some nice techs that have been given with the new support, like returning a summoned Genta, Gateman of Dark World (77895328) to hand with Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World (34230233) or Reign-Beaux, Overking of Dark World (41406613). 

 

The deck is very explosive, but it is possible to brick, unlike Danger Dark world which doesn't brick but relies on luck with dangers. There are pros and cons between using Purrelys in Dark World, and using Dangers in Dark World. Here's some of them.

Pros:

Purrely gives control over your discards, where as dark worlds can either win you the game immediately or lose you the game immediately.

Purrely has amazing access to rank 1 xyz monsters like Lyrilusc - Ensemblue Robin (72971064).

If you don't want to use your purrelys for xyz material, they can still be used as Link Material for Apollousa, I:P, or Muckracker.

They can set up a 2 or 3-activation Zeus very easily, which can win the game on its own.

Expurrely Noir is an Arrival Cyberse @Ignister that also can be interuption, draw you cards, attack multiple monsters with over 7000 attack, or attach opponents monsters to it as material. (These effects mostly come from the quick play spells.)

They're Cute!

Cons:

Purrelys don't give you access to a mass amount of rank 8s, so you lose out on making 38, 90, Felgrand, or Coach King Giantrainer, which draws 3 cards.

Dangers can give you access to as many discards as you need for your darkworlds, but in purrely, you get a limited amount of summons with your quick plays.

Dangers provide many of your draws so that you can get your powerful dark worlds like Snoww or Genta.

You don't have access to Dugares the Timless in this version of the deck. You could make it theoretically by using a genta and a normal summoned level 4, but I've never had a situation where I could do that, or it would be better to do that.

 

Despite the number of cons that the Purrely version of the deck has, I think the Pros outweigh them by a landslide. Of course, feel free to edit the deck to your liking. The side deck is the preference for the upcoming format, though I do recommend Lancea since it can stop some of the Kashtira, floo, and sword soul tenyi cards, as well as shifter and bystials. Unfortunately it doesn't stop shifter on your turn, but it can prevent an otk against some decks.

deck_excerpt: Funny soup made with some funny little guys.
deck_description:
Ojamalphabet Soup

A variation of one of the first decks I've ever played, the first deck I've mastered, and the first deck I loved.

I couldn't find you OP, but thank you so much.

 

Overview

Ojamalphabet Soup is a trainwreck of a deck and only should be played if you don't care to win but just want to have fun and maybe get lucky and sweep a meta deck or two. Every win you get with this deck is earned, you've outplayed your opponent and should be proud of yourself.

You have several goals and options for winning, ABC, XYZ, A-to-Z, and the best but worst of all ADCC.

A quick overview of the deck reveals that 26 of the cards from the main deck are bricks alone. The only one card combos you have are Rescue Cat into Ronin Raccoon/Centurea & Zeus OR Union Hangar into Platinum Gadget & ABC.

This deck cannot function without spell cards, extra deck access, graveyard access, banish zone access, draw power, and ojamas. If you lack one of these things the deck crumbles to nothing but sad, face-down defense position monsters, and an end phase. The key to overcoming this is to believe you will draw something, anything at all.

A playable hand is considered as a single Ojama Blue, even better if you go second and only have Ojama Blue.
A decent hand is Ojama Blue and Ojama Pajama.
A good hand is Ojamagic and Ojamatch.
A great hand is Ojamagic, Ojamatch, Ojamassimilation.
A perfect hand is Ojamagic, Ojamatch, Ojamassimilation x2, and any ojama.

Now before I get into the combos I would like to generally explain what everything in the deck is used for and why it has its place.



Monsters

Ojamas: Firstly, yes I run two sets of the main Ojamas and that's because if you have a single set and draw 1 Ojama, Ojamagic is dead until the Ojama is returned to the deck. Locking off one of your most important cards is not helpful. Blue is at 3 obviously because it's Ojama's best searcher, 2 Red for having two sets of the main Ojamas, Pink at 1 just because you gotta have 'em all. (Also good for digging if you need it. (You do.))
Union: ABCVWXYZ are quite self explanitory, all but ABC are bricks as they are the only ones with useful effects for summoning and searching.
Armed Dragons: These are really only fodder for Ojamatch and summoning LV10, 3 out of the 4 cards here are bricks but, with LV3 you're at least able to start the climb however, without 3 other monsters you can't get much.
Rescue Cat: Rescue Cat doesn't do much other than a surefire way to get Zeus if Ronin Raccoon or Centurea are able to exist.

 

Spell/Trap

Destruction/Backrow: Raigeki, Harpie, and Delta Hurricane are all amazing boardwipes; Delta Hurricane isn't the best card to activate as you need 3 or 5 cards to make this happen, Ojamagic, Ojamatch, and Delta Hurricane, or Red, the 3 main Ojamas, and Delta Hurricane- However, it IS searchable.
Originally the deck had three Twin Twisters but that seemed overkill for discarding and backrow removal, so I cut down to one as I find that to be managable.
Engine: Ojamagic, Ojamatch, Ojamassimilation, and Ojama Pajama are your bread and butter for the deck. Ojamatch to discard Ojamagic to get Red & LV3 is free Saruya & ABC/XYZ. Ojamassimilation can also be used for partial summons with one your two Ojamas for Utopia & Bujin in the sidedeck or a link 2 for Gadget. Union Hangar is guaranteed ABC if drawn so it's very good for creating A-to-Z if you have the right cards.
Duo: Ojama Duo is a very versitile card, you can set it in the event of a sky striker player, activate from grave to summon and xyz/link, OR, the most common: save it in grave as a final protection after your board gets broken.

 

Extra Deck

Fusions: These cards are your lifeline, without these the deck is OVER. First of all, yes VW is trash, don't summon it alone, there is no reason to do so, just go into Utopia. ABC is your main man, with a Quick, OPT Banish effect it's the main, and usually only, choice for interuption. Along with ABC's tag out for material it's great at dodging targets and blocking lots of monsters. Just watch for Called By. XYZ is an occasional usecase, for when ABC banish isn't enough or when ABC is out of commission, XYZ usually has the job covered as long as you have cards in hand to do so, remember Ojamagic gives 3 so it's essentially 4 pops. VWXYZ shouldn't be summoned alone, it's worse ABC, banish a card on the way to ADCC and that's that. But A-to-Z, oh boy, now that's a good card. INFINITE* quick effect omni-negates (*as long as you have cards in hand) on top of the tag out for both ABC and XYZ, there's nothing else to say about this card, it can single handedly shut down your opponent entirely. Finally the biggest baddest fusion of all: ADCC, if you summon this guy, you win. The only if/and/or/but is if it's turn 1 and your opponent hasn't had the chance to put cards on the field, otherwise you're free to absolutely ruin the opponent's day.
XYZ: The classic opening is Rescue Cat turn 1 into Ronin Raccoon with token into your opponent wasting a destruction on Ronin Raccoon because they didn't read the damn card. Anyways these cards are to help you to get Zeus, they're usually just a last resort for stalling/bouncing otherwise.
Link: With two Saryujas you have emmense draw power with your main combo being able to summon BOTH for draw 8 and keep 2, you can basically rotate out your entire hand to get extenders for a possible ADCC. Gadget is only here because of Union Hangar, unfortunately you're out of luck if you want to get XYZ as X isn't a Union monster. Pheonix and Unicorn are the usual toolbox Link monsters for bounce and removal, nothin' special.

 

Side Deck

I'm going to clump the entire sidedeck all together as this is a kit for switching to pure ABC. You have exactly enough cards to swap out VWXYZ in both the main and extra deck for an ABC turbo playstyle, you keep the Armed Dragons for Ojamatch though you can replace LV5, 7, & 10 with Droplet if you need to. This kit is for if you're facing a deck with lots of negates and disruptions that stop you from getting A-to-Z or ADCC. Utopia is here for breaking larger monsters that can't be targeted, and xyz & Link Bujins are here to synergize with Ronin Raccoon and Centurea and dump material and dig for Ojama cards. Added back up is Droplet & D Barrier. While D Barrier can shut down decks like Tear and Despia it also shuts you down, make sure to have a plan when you use this as it could easily screw you over as hard as it does your opponent.

 

Now that we're done with the deck overview, let's go over how you play the damn thing.

 

Combos/Theory

There are two main combos in this deck, every other combo spawns from these in some form.
[A] ends on two Saryuja & ABC/XYZ.
[B] ends on Saryuja, LV10, & ADCC/A-to-Z.


[A] Saryuja^2 & ABC/XYZ
This requires Ojamatch, Ojamagic, and Ojamassimilation* in hand (*It's possible you can draw Ojamassimilation from Saryuja 1's effect so it's not exactly required to start the combo but you will need it for Saruya 2 and ABC.)
Ojamatch discards Ojamagic, search Red & LV3
Ojamagic gives Green, Yellow, & Black
Normal Summon LV3 with Ojamatch
Normal Summon Red
Red Special Summons Green, Yellow, and Black
Link Red, Green, Yellow, and Black into Saryuja
Saryuja draw 4, shuffle 3
Ojamassimilation banishes Green, Yellow, and Black to Special Summon A, B, & C* (*If you choose to summon XYZ, do NOT summon Saryuja 2 as XYZ cannot use materials from the grave to fuse)
Activate Ojamasssimilation in grave to return the banished Ojamas and draw one card
Link LV3, A, B, & C into Saryuja again
Saryuja draw 4, shuffle 3
Ignore A's effect*
B adds W/Y/Z to hand
C doesn't trigger unless you have a union monster in hand (*In the event that this happens you should use A to add B and special summon the Union in hand then B with Saryuja's effect to link into Pheonix and draw another Union from B)
Banish A, B, & C from grave to Fusion Summon ABC

[B] Saruya, LV10 & ADCC/A-to-Z
This requires Ojamatch, Ojamagic, Ojamassimilation x2, and any Ojama monster
Ojamatch discards Ojamagic, search Red & LV3
Ojamagic gives Green, Yellow, & Black
Normal Summon LV3 with Ojamatch
Normal Summon Red
Red Special Summons Green, Yellow, and Black
Link Red, Green, Yellow, and Black into Saryuja
Saryuja draw 4, shuffle 3* (*Be absolutely sure to keep TWO Ojamas in your hand and any monster BUT an Armed Dragon for this to work (For A-to-Z you want 3 Ojamas))
Use the two Ojamas and any monster in hand to Summon LV10 from LV3's effect
Ojamassimilation banishes any three Ojamas to Special Summon X, Y, & Z
Activate Ojamasssimilation in grave to return the banished Ojamas and draw one card
Banish X, Y, & Z from FIELD to Fusion Summon XYZ
Ojamassimilation banishes the other two Ojamas to Special Summon V & W* (*Or three for ABC if you're going for A-to-Z)
Banish V & W to Fusion Summon VW
Banish VW & XYZ to Fusion Summon VWXYZ (Rememeber to banish for free!)
Banish VWXYZ from Field and LV7 from GY to Fusion Summon ADCC

These two combos are your BnBs for the deck, Ojamatch and Ojamagic get you Saryuja for digging and three Ojamas plus Ojamassimilation can get you just about anything from the extra deck. Don't restrict yourself to these two combos, if you need to use Pheonix & Unicorn instead of Saryuja 2, go for it. If you want to Utopia, send it. The deck is flexible to an extent where you can get anything as long as you have the right circumstances but it takes a little work to get there.

A piece of tech to end this off is the secret third combo:
[C] Ojama Blue Car Crash
If you only have Blue and you can attack do this:
Normal Summon Blue
Proceed to Attack Phase
Crash Blue into an ATTACK position monster* (*This does not work against defense position monsters)
Blue activates and you Search Ojamatch & Ojamagic
Ojamatch discards Ojamagic to search Blue and an Armed Dragon
Ojamatch Normal Summons Blue
Crash Blue AGAIN
Blue activates and you search Ojamatch & Ojama Duo
Ojamatch discards Ojama Duo to search Blue again and another Armed Dragon
Crash Blue AGAIN to finally search two Ojamassimilations
From here, do what you must.

 

Conclusion

Overall, this deck blows. It's not very consistent, however it is very fun. The most fun I've had since I've started playing was with this deck. And let me tell you, it feels so good to banish a player's entire field and grave with ADCC it's like a drug. Knowing that they probably didn't read your card, knowing that next turn they can't activate their cards or effects and slowly they'll realize and you see the horror crawl upon their face as they read ADCC and then surrender. What a glorious deck. Outplaying your opponent feels like an achievement each time, baiting negates and destructions only to reveal an Ojamatch or Ojamassimilation in the back. If you've come this far, give it a try. A few games won't hurt. Who knows, maybe you'll grow an appreciation for the deck or maybe you'll laugh at me for playing something so garbage in competitive formats. Whatever your choice is I hope you enjoyed your time here. Thank you.

deck_excerpt: 1,5 card full board lock, unoptimised list
deck_description:
This is an unoptimized list to achieve a full board lock. The combo starts with "Lonefire blossom" or "Predaplant Ophrys Scorpico" and a monster you can send to the GY in hand.

Cards that can't be send: "Angel O7", "The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots", any "Naturia" Monster

 

 

To start of the combo you need to summon "Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio" with one monster in hand to activate his effect.

If you have 2 "Makyura the Destructor" in hand you need to discard one of them here.

Summon "Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra" and add "Fusion Gate" to your hand. Link them off for "Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss" and activate its effect to send "Graph, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss" to the GY.

Activate "Graph, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss" to summon "Cir, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss" and link summon "The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche".

Activate the effect of "Cir, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss" and summon "Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss" from your GY.

Use the effect of "The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche" to set "The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigadine" to your side of the field by sending "The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak" to the GY.

If you don't have "The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots" in your hand search it by using "The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak" in your GY.

Special summon "The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots" from your hand and activate "The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigadine" to link them off for "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights".

Add "Elemental HERO Sparkman" to your hand.

Activate the effect of "The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots" to add "Phantom Knights' Spear" to your hand.

Use the effect of "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights", not sending "Broken Bamboo Sword" to summon "Armageddon Knight" to a any Monster Zone not being the middle one.

Send "Summoner Monk" to the GY and add "Broken Bamboo Sword" to your hand.

Link Summon "Aleister the Invoker of Madness" using "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights" and "Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss".

Activate Fusion Gate to Summon "Elemental HERO Escuridao" using "Elemental HERO Sparkman" and "The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche".

Link Summon "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians" using "Elemental HERO Escuridao" and "Aleister the Invoker of Madness" as material.

Remove 3 Spell Counters form "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians" to summon "Summoner Monk" and use his effect to summon "Makyura the Destructor" by discarding "Broken Bamboo Sword".

Link Summon "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians" using "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians", "Summoner Monk" and "Makyura the Destructor" as material and activate the effect of "Makyura the Destructor".

Remove 3 Spell Counters form "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians" to summon "Summoner Monk" and use his effect to summon "Recue Ferret" by discarding "Phantom Knights' Spear".

Use the effect of "Recue Ferret" to summon "Two-for-one Team" and any 4-Star "HERO".

Fusion summon "Mudragon of the Swamp" using "wo-for-one Team" and "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians".

Summon "Primathmech Alembertian" to the EMZ using all monsters on the field as material und use his effect to search "Chain Material".

Activate "Chain Material" from your hand with the effect of "Makyura the Destructor".

Summon "Idaten the Conqueror Star" using "Elemental HERO Escuridao" and "Yoko-Zuna Sumo Spirit" material.

Summon "The Dark Magicians" using "Summoner Monk" and "Dark Magician" as Material.

Now begins an endless card draw loop:

 

Activate Fusion Gate to summon "Elemental HERO Electrum"

Draw one card of "The Dark Magicians"

Summon "Idaten the Conqueror Star" using "Idaten the Conqueror Star" and "Elemental HERO Electrum" as material

Summon "The Dark Magicians" using "The Dark Magicians" and "Dark Magician" as Material

 

Loop until you draw "Naturia Tulip", "Naturia Bamboo Shoot", "Chow Sai the Ghost Stopper", "Necrovalley", "Angel O7", "Fog King", "Zany Zebra", "Card Advance", "Yoko-Zuna Sumo Spirit", "Kai-Den Kendo Spirit", "Chain Summoning" and 2 "Ground Collapse"

 

Place "Yoko-Zuna Sumo Spirit" and "Kai-Den Kendo Spirit" as your Pend Scales and Pend Summon "Chow Sai the Ghost Stopper" and "Naturia Tulip"

Upon the activation of the Scales activate "Chain Summoning" as CL 3.

Activate "Card Advance" and use the additional Tribute Summon to summon "Naturia Bamboo Shoot", tributing "Naturia Tulip".

Activate the 2 "Ground Collapse" to block 4 Monster Zones of your opponent, then "Zany Zebra" in the Pend Zone to block the last one.

Tribute Summon "Angel O7", activate "Necrovalley", then summon "Fog King".

The Board is now fully locked

deck_excerpt: A self-made structure deck for casual game nights.
deck_description:
A project I'm theory crafting. A MTG player returning to Yugioh with the 25th anniversiy, very new to modern Yugioh, I wanted to make my own structure decks to essemble a self contained item for casual board game nights. Sure the structure decks from Konami are great, but where is the penguin deck! With returning to Yugioh its awesome to see all the different archtypes and especially the elevation of goofy OG cards like Penguin Soldier.

My rules are to make sure to include as many archtype cards as possible. Avoid full playsets so decks are not super consistent. Include a few staples (Ash, Maxx, etc) for interaction. Possibly include another archtype (or their staples) if they have synergy.  

Any suggestions to make this deck more fun and at a similar power level with modern structures decks would be appreciated.

project I'm theory crafting. A MTG player returning to Yugioh with the 25th anniversiy, very new to modern Yugioh, I wanted to make my own structure decks to essemble a self contained item for casual board game nights. This is the second deck I've made, and as a fan of little idiots I had to make an Ojama deck. I wanted this deck to not be Ojama Soup deck, with Machines and Armed Dragons, but to focus on Ojama fusions and spells.

My rules are to make sure to include as many archtype cards as possible. Avoid full playsets so decks are not super consistent. However, I ran closer with this list then my penguin deck due to really need OG Ojamas. Include a few staples (Ash, Maxx, etc) for interaction. Possibly include another archtype (or their staples) if they have synergy.  

Any suggestions to make this deck more fun and at a similar power level with modern structures decks would be appreciated.

deck_excerpt: Pure Lyrilusc for XYZ Festival in Master Duel
deck_description: Pure Lyrilusc for XYZ Festival in Master Duel

Evil Eye got 2 new cards of support in Photon Hypernova and they are really powerful. Evil eye has always been a tower/control deck, and these 2 new cards don't change up that playstyle while also making the deck more consistent.

A typical endboard usually contains a monster equiped with the Evil Eye of Selene(either Serziel or Gorgon), some backrow/hand traps, and the new spell and monster in the GY. What do they do you ask?

Well Unleashed is a double foolish FOR COST that searches an Evil Eye equip. The usual sent cards are Gorgoneio and Basiltrice. Gorgoneio can banish itself and pitch an evil eye to search any spell/trap, and Basiltrice can special itself as a quick effect and during the opponents turn link summon an Evil Eye monster. And when you link summon an evil eye, you banish Unleashed to re-equip the equip in the gy to the new monster who now gains their eff. 

While this strategy has a low ceiling, the monster can be very stickey and it is very consistent. You have Serziel who searches anything, the field spell which searches any monster, Gorgoneio which searches any spell/trap, and both Pots that round out that consistency. 

While it might not look that cheap, most of the budget is going into the powerful staples. Seriously in this build, the 3 Pot of Prosperities cost more than the rest of the deck combined. And the deck has no real weaknesses to the common boardbreakers or hand traps running around right now. Lava golem is usually dead here, d-shifter is annoying but isnt necessarily a turn ender, and evenly actually can be played around by using Basiltrice on field summon effect in response to evenly to only have to banish the backrow, then in a new chain you re-equip the Eye. 

All in All, I see this deck being rouge competitive at best, and definitly the option for the budget minded(Again, if you take out the Pot of Prosperities, the price drops by almost $200)

Going second we have Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Effect Veiler, Infinite Impermanence, Triple Tactics Talent and Kashtira Fenrir.   

 

The Magistus Engine 

Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame is powerful card that shines brightest during grind games, but also allows you to shut down your opponents important extra deck monster effects during turn one (if you know what you are up against), by equipping itself with Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden, Special Summoning an Aleister the Invoker, Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous, Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires or searching for Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires with the effect of Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden and Special Summoning him by sending a Spellcaster from your hand or field to the GY, Synchro Summoning Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity and equipping itself with the relevant Magistus Extra Deck Monster.

Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires can also banish itself from the GY to equip Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity with Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden to deny access to Link Monster effects. You can also choose to hold on to Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires's GY effect to re-equip the actually needed extra deck Magistus Monster.

If you don't know what you are up against, it's best to go the Invoked route - which you will be able to do more often anyway.

Don't forget: Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity can also Special Summon himself from the GY by destroying a Magistus Card in your Spell/Trap Zone. Even if you rarely Synchro Summon Vahram, the Magistus Divinity Dragon, you should remember his board wipe ability on destruction. However, I have never XYZ Summoned Ninaruru, the Magistus Glass Goddess.

Fun Fact: Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires is an out to Gozen Match as it can change its own Attribute to the Attribute you need to keep on playing. Most of the time it will be Fire or Light.

Deck Synergies:

  • After searching with Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden, you can send her to the GY with Magicians' Souls to draw one card.
  • If you open with Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame, Invocation and Aleister the Invoker you can end on Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity and Invoked Mechaba or Invoked Purgatrio after 4 Summons with Nibiru Protection.
  • Effect Veiler is a Spellcaster that can be sent to the GY to Special Summon Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires. It is also a Level 1 Tuner that theoretically allows you to use it and Kashtira Fenrir to go into Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity if you somehow bricked and can make the call, that Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity would actually be better than Kashtira Fenrir on the field and Effect Veiler in the hand.
  • You can also use Invocation to Fusion Summon Aiwass, the Magistus Spell Spirit which can take control over an opponent's monster.

 

The Invoked Engine

With 7 Starters for this Archetype, you will more often than not open with this. Going first you can almost always guarantee having access to Invoked Mechaba by Link Summoning Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden with Aleister the Invoker.

Use Invoked Mechaba to hit their key card activations. Keep in mind that you can't negate the effects of continuous Spell/Trap Cards or Field Spells - only their initial activation. The upside is, that the negation banishes and is once per copy. So if you control two Invoked Mechaba you can use the effect of each copy to negate cards during each round.

Invoked Purgatrio is your going second / grind game beatdown Boardbreaker who benefits from cards like Book of Eclipse in the Side Deck.
The Invoked Engine has a pretty straightforward but rewarding play style if you manage your resources (mostly hand cards for negates).

Deck Synergies:

  • Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden, Effect Veiler, Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous, Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted and Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires (after changing his own Attribute to Light) can be used as material to Fusion Summon Invoked Mechaba if your opponent doesn't have Light Monsters in his GY.
  • Salamangreat Almiraj, Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame, Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires (after changing his own Attribute to Fire) can be used to Fusion Summon Invoked Purgatrio if you opponent doesn't have Fire Monsters in his GY.
  • After Fusion Summoning, you can send Magical Meltdown to the GY with Magicians' Souls to draw one card.
  • If you have no other option, you can send Aleister the Invoker to the GY with his own effect to guarantee a Dark Monster in your GY for Fusion Summoning El Shaddoll Winda with Shaddoll Schism.

 

The Dogmatika Engine 


Next to Kashtira Fenrir, Nadir Servant is probably the best card in this deck. It allows you to search for Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous and Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted from Deck or GY, set up your El Shaddoll Winda Lock or pop a card with Elder Entity N'tss. If used after already accessing your Extra Deck, the restriction doesn't bother you at all.

It is an over all strong Archetype that doesn't really rely on the other Archetypes to shine.

Deck Synergies:

  • Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous is a Level 4 Spellcaster, so she can be Special Summoned by Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame.
  • Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous can Special Summon herself so you don't loose your normal summon.
  • Nadir Servant sets up the El Shaddoll Winda Lock by sending El Shaddoll Apkallone to the GY.
  • Nadir Servant or Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous combinded with Terraforming, Magical Meltdown or Aleister the Invoker can deal up to 8,500 damage.
  • You can use Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden or Salamangreat Almiraj to have an Extra Deck Monster on the field in order to Special Summon Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous (if you otherwise bricked).

 

The Magicians' Souls Engine 

Deck Synergies:

  • You can send Shaddoll Schism to the GY with Magicians' Souls to draw one card.
  • Sending Illusion of Chaos to the GY always gurantees a Dark Monster in your GY for your El Shaddoll Winda Lock
  • If you can manage your Extra Deck better than me, you can also run three Pot of Prosperity instead of this 5 Card Engine.

 

The Side Deck

You should always keep an eye on the current meta for the Side Deck.

However, Nibiru, the Primal Being for going second and Summon Limit for going first hit a wide variety of meta and rouge decks in a lot of formats. If you find yourself being locked by your own Summon Limit, you can send it to the GY with Magicians' Souls to draw one card. After turn one, you rarely summon more than twice.
Going first I usually side out Effect Veiler for Summon Limit or/and Dimensional Barrier (mostly against Branded).

 

Powerful Opening Hand Going First 

Kashtira Fenrir, Magical Meltdown, Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame, Invocation and Nadir Servant

You end on Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity, Invoked Mechaba, Kashtira Fenrir, Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous, Shaddoll Schism and in hand have Kashtira Fenrir + Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted (or a set Dogmatika Punishment)
That leaves you with 2 Monster Negates, at least one Type of Extra Deck Monster Effect blocked from activation, Schism Destruction, Winda Lock, Banish facedown after Monster Effect activation.
Took some ideas, merged them together. Then Chris Hanson appeared for some reason..

deck_excerpt: Budget friendly and highly competitive Ninja deck. Devastating in the right pilots hands.
deck_description:
The side deck is almost half the price, so just leave it out if you want to keep it extra budget friendly. I do, however, strongly recommend you get Solemn Judgment. The Extra Deck monsters (besides Meizen the Battle Ninja, Yaguramaru the Armor Ninja and Ninja Grandmaster Saizo) are not necessary, but do allow you to extend your plays and finish off games early. Book of Moon can be replaced with Book of Eclipse, but I advise against it, at least until you really know what you're doing. Note that Instant Fusion and Millennium-Eyes Restrict are optional and can be swapped for whatever you prefer instead, but they basically represent a free negate and this shouldn't be slept on.

You can opt to run Pot of Extravagance at one or two, but I don't recommend running three copies (you can also play Pot of Prosperity - a better, but way more expensive option). Cards you should also consider running include, but are not limited to: Accesscode Talker, I:P Masquerena, Book of Eclipse, Harpie's Feather Duster, Appointer of the Red Lotus...

Note that this isn't one of the decks that just plays itself and does require an experienced pilot to be played at its full potential. This is why I recommend you join the Ninja Discord Community listed below, where you can find incredible resources and first-hand advice from Ninja players.

Join the Ninja Discord community to learn more: https://discord.com/invite/5kDFRsr

deck_excerpt: When I say this deck has a Towers, I mean it's literally a tower of cards.
deck_description:
This is a deck I have been using at locals and wanted to share some thoughts before the new support release.

 

The main goal is to make Expurrely Noir with a lot of materials. Easiest way usually is to summon Purrely, then go for Plump, attatch 2 cards from the GY, and activate another quick play for 5 material on Plump. Ideally, the Noir should have at least 2 Delicious Memory as material to be difficult to attack over for most decks. Since the Expurrelys cannot equip quick plays like the Epurrelys can, the field spell can provide a few extra material to make the Noir as big as possible.

Expurrely Happiness does not have as much of an impact in most games, but is good for summoning off Yeap in the Battle Phase to push for damage and make a Zeus. The DRNM effect is cool but rarely comes up, as you'd probably make a Noir in most situations.

The Purrely cards in the main take up about half the deck, so the other half has a lot of room to work with for options. I've been using a small Rescue-ACE package as a draw engine. Fire Attacker is great if your opponent summons a monster that searches and can activate every turn if it survives. Delicious and Happy Memories both need a card on the field to resolve (Delicious needs a monster) so having one on your side to choose for the effects can be good to get combos going too.

I played a lot of monster stealing stuff partly because it paired well with the effect of Pretty Memory's material effect. They are good tools for pressuing an opponent's board and if you can steal a monster you can attatch a different card they control by using the monster you stole.

The Extra is primarily focused on Purrely. 2 of each name is good in case you can't turbo into Noir and need to rebuild. The only HOPT effects in Purrely are the continuous spell and the trap so it's not impossible to recover from losing your Purrely. Downerd + Zeus make big Zeus. Assembled Nightingale and Linkuriboh are nice if your Purrely effect gets negated on summon and you don't have any quick plays in hand already.

The Side has mostly anti-Kash cards. Spooky Dogwood is for playing into time and Evenly is just good. I had Lighting Storm in previously and may return it for more backrow hate.

 

This deck is probably not a meta contender yet but has had good performances in the OCG with the new support. For now though, it still has good tools for controling the board and staying alive to build up your Purrely if you can't make Noir in 1 turn. This also deck has a distinct lack of HOPT effects. The biggest problem I think is it's difficult to maintain card advantage as you can discard a lot to use the quick plays. Also, this deck struggles if too many Purrelys get banished, such as from Bystials or Desires.
Ninja (Feb 2023)

Deck consistency is incredible, hadn't brick a single hand during the tournament (64 players) and got top 1. I mixed Libromancer with Dogmatika and Invoke previously but it was quite bad since there were no synergies in three 3 archetypes, but this one hit differently. For PK, you can link any 2mons into Aleister madness + Linku/Lingu then into Rusty and set those 2 Fog blades. Give this deck a shot, it won't let you down.

deck_name: Dinomist + Dracoslayer | A.K.A. | Dracomist | All Gas/Fun Build | Budget Deck |
deck_excerpt: A cheap, fun fast-n-loose way to play Dinomists. The Dracoslayers are consistent and give ExD access. Best part? It's technically archetypal
deck_description:
THIS IS A BUDGET BUILD

Ideally you'd be playing beyond the pend, access code etc. I'm poor. The deck is ok.

In testing this deck I realised that you usually can't end on a substantial board if you don't use basically your entire hand, so the best ways to play this deck are either guns blasing or using tons of floodgates; but forget about that last part because we're here to have fun! 

This is a very, very, very monster heavy build. Its basically just monsters and spells, and those spells also get into monsters, so yeah, I wasn't kidding when I said all gas

The dracoslayers are very consistent. They all either recur, search or special one another. You usually want to open with two-three dracoslayers, one of which should e ignis or powerload.

 

know when to quit

If you open vector+faceoff, double igknight reload, double charge, either make a negate or bagoo and pass,or straight up scoop. You cannot pop off without a hand full of names

 

Gameplan:

If you open only dinomists, you can usually end on Bahamut + Toad + Cy-Dra Infinity. for really lucky hands you cand end those three plus Abyss Dweller and cross sheep but those combo lines are a bit complicated. It's a pendulum deck folks, it's not gonna come easy.

You'll usually open with an even split of dinos and dracos. if you have ignis and either luster or pegasus, use either of their effects to pop ignis and summon whichever draconame(s) you didn't open with from deck. either normal a guy or scale powerload and summon the other scale. Using those two, make cross sheep. You want to make cross sheep before pend-ing. Always. always make sure you pend a copy of luster; prominance is probably the best archytypal ExD monster in the deck and luster is the only tuner except for niche ignis shenanigans. With Prominances effect you'll want to get a powerload as you'll be making Dinoster in the cross-sheep zone. When you make Dinoster using powerload, make sure you have pegasus in extra; Use her as the other fusion mat if you must. This is where you'll use the effect of powerload getting back pegasus to hand. Use the hand effect of pegasus to discard and protect dracos for the turn. The protection is nice, but you mainly want it to special it from grave with dinoster's effect. mediocre hands might end there, but if you have another extender you can make paladin. special ignis with paladin's effect to the unused cross-sheep zone in case you have to float on your opponents turn. During the end phase you can take pegasus with paladins effect so you can use the hand effect of pegasus on your opponents turn and protect your big guys.

Techs

ONE field spell.

      In my personal deck I play a copy of the field spell. Cross sheep can help recover the discard so its basically a free card if you play right. We love free cards. The field spell isn't great, but pegasus searches any field spell. If you're a floodgate enjoyer, play zombie world or necrovally, but I like the thematic FS.

Dinomist Howling.

      I know it's a gas build, but it is super satisfing to tribute powerload for howling with charge on the field. Going plus 3 on a continuous compulsury evac devise is orgasmic.

Called by the grave

      Like all mid decks that feel great when you pop off, ash ruins this deck. You can setup through veiler usually, but ash? No. 

 

Anyway. You won't be winning any events, you probably mightn't even make day 2, Hell, you'll probably get your sh*t mixed by a 4 year old playing a floo deck they traded their happy meal for at your locals, but if you just play with friends and locals you'll have a blast losing to getting evenly matched for your whole board + your life savings + your house + your wife + your kids + and your job, which is what I plan to do once I find other girls who play yu-gi-oh. But man, this deck is fun, complex, cheap(most importantly. The whole deck is like 30 dollars including extra. And 15 of that is exclusivly Cy-Dra Infin and x3 ignis alone) the monsters and lore are pretty cool, and I want to be luster pendulum's and ignis pheonix's wife. Luster, baby, please text me back. I love you.
Runick is fun.

deck_excerpt: Best version of Dinosaur for February 23 format
deck_description:
This 60-card version is a great option for playing Dinosaur in the current format. You always choose to go second and it has an engine with good consistency and lots of tech cards to help you break the field and establish yours or simply OTK.

 

///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Clarifying the Scrap Raptor engine:

I have already mentioned more than once even in this Dinosaur article how much the Scrap engine helps the deck in several weaknesses.

1 - The first is the question of accessing Omega to return Miscellaneosaurus to the GY.

2 - The second is that you have more 2 card combo options because it works in conjunction with Lost World and Miscellaneousaurus.

3 - The third is that it gives you a lot of versatility on the end board. So you can choose to do 1 LINK + 1 XYZ RANK-4 + 1 Synchro-8 or to access 2 Synchro-8 or even 3 XYZ RANK-4.

4 - Scrap Wyvern is not only a combo piece but interaction against the opponent destroying cards without targeting. Even this engine works even if you are on floodgates like Gozen Match and There Can Be Only One.

5 - And you do combo even if you draw 1 Scrap Raptor being their main advantage not only more summons to make more extra deck monsters but mainly for you to access Evolzar Dolkka before starting any other extra deck summon protecting yourself from hand traps.

6 - In short, with a well-built deck, you can make this engine much more productive than thinking it's a brick in your hand, and now that we have access to 2 more card combo through the Xeno Ground spell, Scrap Raptor becomes even better for be the second best target on the card.

 

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ///////////////Now I'll leave below Combos and Test Hand of this version:

(there are several combos that you can learn by looking at my last deck profiles about this deck - https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/dinosaur-scrap-318392)

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-47198686

TEST HAND 0 - 60card Scrap Dinosaur Combo

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46901533

COMBO 1: Diagram + Oviraptor/Babycerasaurus = (End Board with Omega - MORE RECOMMENDED)

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46961340

COMBO 2: Lithosagym + 2 Babycerasaurus/Petiteranodon = (FULL COMBO WITH OMEGA - BEST END BOARD - you could also have done Lambda)

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46961128

COMBO 2.1: Lithosagym + Babycerasaurus/Petiteranodon + any Monster = (End Board Full Combo with Omega - you could also have done Lambda)

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46962458

COMBO 3: Lost World + Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus/Petiteranodon = (Play around Hand Traps and have Follow Ups)

 

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ////////////Theory behind Small World:

Small World is basically a consistency card for the deck, there are several combinations of main deck monsters that you can banish and add Miscellaneousaurus to your hand.

Miscellaneousaurus is an unfair card and helps the deck a lot so having access to it in an easy way is very important.

For example Small World reveal Ash Blossom you can add Miscellaneosaurus or Archosaur. Also works with Babycerasaurus and PSY-Framegear Gamma. Among other different combinations involving in addition to hand traps also Kaiju for example since the main main deck monsters have different attributes.
Improved Version of 3x SD Beware of Traptrix

deck_excerpt: Final version of Mathmech Dinosaur using the excellent G Golem LINK Monsters
deck_description:
Mathmech Scrap Dino is a very interesting version of Dinosaur. The deck is based on the fact that you can access Mathmech Circular through Primathmech Alembertian and in synergy with cyberse monsters that the deck already accesses in the combo like Linkuriboh you do the same combo from Linkross' time in the game on Mathmech.

That way you can play normally from Scrap Dino and shape your final field to access the 3 Mathmech monsters in the GY with Superfactorial to get an excellent end board that plays around all the blind second cards at the same time that you always end up with Omega which means returning Miscellaneosaurus to the GY. In this version of the deck you bring Pankratops with Double Evolution Pill because you can activate Superfactorial even after Dark Ruler No More by tributing Pankratops just to have 3 spaces available on the field and do Laplacian.

It is because of this detail that I use only 1 Ultimate Conductor Tyranno since he is a follow up card in turn 3 of the game. Among the deckbuild details, the main changes I made were using the G Golem engine, which in this deck makes a lot of sense because your extra deck is already made up of Cyberse monsters and they improve and make possible several combos in the deck. I think this engine manages to be better than the version of this deck with Spright Elf that I had made when the card was not banned. The second major change is adding Ash Blossom by lowering Lost World and Prosperity that synergizes with Small World, so Small World has multiple ways to add Miscellaneousaurus to the hand.

In the extra deck I consider almost all the necessary cards, the only flex spot I consider would be Lambda and Apollousa that you can use instead of I:P Masquerena or Splash Mage. In general, I use almost all the extra deck cards on the first turn, usually leaving 3 to 5 cards. That's why Prosperity can only be used for 3 cards in the deck.

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ///////GAMEPLAY TEST HAND

 

I consider the plays involving this engine in a lot of detail for each combo you should pay attention to. Depending on each combination of cards, you'll make combos using cards and card activation sequences that completely change the end board or that, if done in the wrong order, don't allow you to build anything.

This deck has a very cool concept and unlike any other approach to the Dinosaur engine, it has consistency and you will definitely be able to have a lot of fun with it.

 

Main points to pay attention to:

1 - Use the following website to find out the possible combinations with Small World in the deck: https://small-world.yugioh-api.com/resolve

2 - Restrictions on Mathmech monsters: you get lock on Extra Deck Cyberse if you use Mathmech Sigma eff. And whenever you use Mathmech Circular's effect you can only attack with one monster in the Battle Phase.

TEST HAND 2 - Using Lithosagym Combo Destroy 1 Babycerasaurus/Petiteranodon (If you do Omega instead of Dolkka Miscellaneousaurus would return in the GY)

 

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ///////Scrap Dino Ogdoadic:

Technoplay: Whenever you're doing combos, think about playing around Nibiru, the Primal Being in combos involving the Scrap Raptor engine, sometimes it's better to use Scrap Raptor on yourself to add Scrap Chimera than risk going to Scrap Wyvern .

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46971627

Archosaur + Babycerasaurus = Example what you can do after Nibiru when the Spright Elf are legal in the game.

Before it was possible when the absurd and insane Spright Elf was the best generic support available in the deck you didn't have to worry about it because you put Giant Rex and Token together in I:P Masquerena and then made Spright Elf using Oviraptor and I :P Masquerena to Reborn the Scrap Wyvern since the opponent controls Nibiru and you manage to use your 1st and 2nd effect to bring Scrap Raptor from deck and destroy Nibiru thus managing to finish with Spright Elf + Dolkka or Lambda + Tyranno and in the opponent's turn Reborn from Petiteranodon or I:P Masquerena to have one more interaction against the opponent in the form of Knightmare Unicorn or Pankratops or bring in Oviraptor and add Tyranno to the hand. That is, it doesn't make any difference to take Nibiru when you had access to Spright Elf in the deck but now that's not possible and you should play very well around hand traps, especially Nibiru.

 

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ///////Some rules:

 

Mekk-Knight Purple nightfall vs Book of Moon/Ultimate Conductor Tyranno

Chain Link 1: Purple nightfall attempts to banish itself

Chain Link 2: Book of Moon/Ultimate Conductor Tyranno attempts to flip it face down.

Does nightfall still get banned?

It is banished face-down, and returns to the field in face-down Defense Position. Temporary banishment banishes the monster as it is.

 

Number 23: Lancelot, Dark Knight of the Underworld

"Once per turn, during either player's turn, when a Spell/Trap Card, or another monster's effect is activated: Detach 1 Xyz Material from this card; negate the activation."

This effect is a MANDATORY Quick Effect. (This effect also activates during the Damage Step. Detaching 1 Xyz Material from this card is a cost to activate this effect.)

In short it is a MANDATORY effect so it will be activated whenever the first spell/trap or monster effect is used and it can negate your own cards too so be very careful when using it in the deck to not end up negating your own cards on your turn, to to avoid this always do it at the end of the combo after activating all your cards.

 

////////////////////////////////////////////////// ////////Enemy Controller is the main deck card that you can exchange for any other tech card like Book of Eclipse for example.

The labrynth cards (chandraglier, stovie torbie, cooclock) can activate their effects to allow for the bystials to be used whenever even if the opponent isn't playing lights/darks.

Main reason I built this deck was because I wanted to have a way for Labrynth to go into Slifer the Sky Dragon. The bystials are 6s that can go into Beatrice and Lady Lab can search any trap including The Revived Sky God. Lovely Lab will be able to reset it every turn so you can have Slifer every turn. This combo is very unlikely to pull off but that is where the inspiration came from. Using the Bystials as big bodies to hit the opponent with also works.

This traptrix deck utilises the new support from the new structure deck 'Beware of the Traptrix. This deck also utilises select Springans and Therion engines. The main line in combos is to link summon into Aromaseraphy Jasmin using a monster and Traptrix Sera (which may sound strange but you can special summon Traptrix Sera from the graveyard using Traptrix Holeutea's effect). You can then use Aromaseraphy Jasmine's effect to destroy a Rikka Queen Strenna to special summon Therion Lily Borea from the deck. Rikka Queen Strenna's effect will chain to special summon Sacred Tree Beast, Hypertron. Then you Activate Therion Lily Borea's effect to tribute itself to add Therion Discollesium, which searches Therion King Regulus. This gives you two negates and likely two set trap hole traps. 

If Pot Of Prosperity is too expensive, you can replace it with a Traptrix Pudica and two Hole normal traps.An extra Gravedigger's Trap Hole and Floodgate Trap Hole are probabely the most optimal to add to the deck. 

I hope you enjoy this deck

Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Creighton "Kaiju King" Pree

Tournament: Shreveport WCQ Regional- February 25th 2023

Placement: 1st Place

Today we take a closer look at the ominous Icejade Archetype. It's known to be the worst within the Albaz Storyline. But I'm here to tell you otherwise today. Let's Start! 

Everything you need to know about this Pure Variant can also be found in the Video linked below^^ 

 

Unfreezing your Deck

Many cards in this Deck bring your Strategy up to speed. We have the Draw 1 Monster Icejade Acti , the Spell & Trap searcher Icejade Aegirine , the one card LV10 synchro enabler Icejade Aegirine Rahn , the Hand unbricking tool with Icejade Tremora and the High Level searcher Crystal Girl. And that's just the Monsters. 

The Spell Icejade Cradle searches for any Icejade Monster without a Once Per Turn. Icejade Manifestation brings Icejade's from your Deck directly onto field or into the Graveyard and Icejade Erosion can do similar if the opponent removes Monsters from your field. More on that comes later. 

So in Total you have a big amount of Tools to get everything you want whenever you want. 

 

Trapped in the Lockdown

The Icejade Archetype is known for his formidable lockdown for a reason. It should almost always be your first priority to setup the Lockdown. It involves 3 Cards which are the LV10 Boss Monster Icejade Kosmochlor your field spell Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle and your permanent spell Icejade Curse. With those 3 on field your opponent cannot activate Monster effects on the field ever. It targets your opponent and not the Monsters which makes this kind of effect unavoidable. 

Icejade Kosmochlor can special summon herself when a Field Spell is active on the field and with 3K defense and the ability to further weaken opponents Monsters by 1000 for every Kosmochlor on the field it is hard to remove in Battle. The Field Spell Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle can also weaken all opposing Monsters if a Monster is summoned. Lastly the Icejade Curse has a built in Burn effect if a Monster is destroyed by Battle involving your Icejade Monster. 

So far so good but it's easy to remove with generic Removal or Kaijus right? ..... right?...

 

The Almighty Icejade Wall

Icejade just might be the most difficult Wall to overcome once established. After setting up your lockdown what remains is to make sure nobody can Break through it. 

You have 3 different Monsters operating from.the GY which are Icejade Tremora , Icejade Tinola and Icejade Acti . Whenever a Water Monster is Destroyed you can Banish them to Special summon a Icejade Monster from your Hand or GY. Your Field Spell Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle can recycle your Banished Icejade's back to Hand when activated to keep this Recycling loop online a long time. 

The Trap Icejade Erosion can Destroy one of your Icejade's to Negate any Face Up Card on the field which might threaten your Backrow. If your opponent should use a Kaiju or other means of non destruction Removal the 2nd effect of Erosion comes into play. When a Icejade leaves the field except by being destroyed you can Special an Icejade Monster directly from your Deck or you add it to your Hand. 

Lastly your LV10 Synchro Boss Icejade Gymir Aegirine can prevent Destruction and Banishing of your Monsters as a Quick effect and non targeting remove Threats from the opponent. 

You might have noticed by now that a perfect Icejade Board achieves something very unique. A virtually unbreakable Board with a unavoidable Lockdown. 

 

The Icy Trickbox

There's still more stuff this Deck can do so let's talk about it. I haven't mentioned it but both Icejade Tinola and Icejade Gymir Aegirine have built in Revival effects on top of the other things they can do. Icejade Aegirine Rahn can treat herself as the Field Spell while she's equipped with a Equip Card. 

Icejade Creation Aegirocassis and Icejade Creation Kingfisher can both equip themselves to Icejade Monsters. The Aegirocassis can do it from the GY too, making him the perfect discard outlet ane at the same time a nice target for Icejade Erosion due to his special summoning effect. Also gaining 400 ATK and DEF for every banished Monster will create very strong Icejade Monsters. 

The Kingfisher enables Icejade's to attack while in defense Position and can Bounce opponents Monster's. His Equipping effect is also not a once per turn. He's best used in Combination with Icejade Kosmochlor . 

Icejade Manifestation can Banish opponents cards if he removes your monsters except by destroying them and Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying can further Banish opponents cards and weaken them, while increasing his Strength. He's like handwritten for the Archetype. 

The remainibg cards really are up to preference and can be switched around as you like. 

 

The Cradle breaks apart

As good as all of this sounds, if you are unable to establish the Lockdown or the opponent removes it before you can activate your defensive tools you are pretty much done for. Beware of the usual offenders which cripple other Strategys too. 

 

Icejade's Final Verdict

The Icejade Strategy has come a long way in recent years and is quite formidable if played right. Be sure to give it a try if you like Defensive Style Gameplay. They are fun. 

 

Overall Rating: 驕驕驕驕驕驕

deck_excerpt: 3 engines combined to form a deck that can easily compete with todays meta.
deck_description:
The scareclaw engine is very consistent. It uses one card combos and can easily OTK your opponent using tri-heart, or set up a decent board by using cards like baronne de fleur and scareclaw sclash.

The adventure engine does not conflict with the deck at all, since you only use your normal summon to make scareclaw light-heart. This engine also helps to activate the additional effects of scareclaw cards by having more defense position monsters.

The kashtira engine allows this deck to be more consistent by searching out scareclaw kashtira. Additionally, kashtira fenrir can be used as an interruption for your opponent or extra material for link summoning.

This deck also makes use of triple tactics thrust to be able to search reinforcement of the army, rite of aramesir, or terraforming, allowing access to any one of the three engines.

Overall this deck combines the three engines of scareclaw adventure and kashtira into a deck that functions very well and can easily compete with today's meta.
